## DESCRIPTION
## Michigan precalculus gateway problem: topic solving linear systems
## ENDDESCRIPTION

DOCUMENT();
loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "PGchoicemacros.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl"
);

Context("Numeric");

# disallow partial credit for gateway problems
install_problem_grader(~~&std_problem_grader);

## solution:
##   x - y = a,
##   c x - d y = e, or (d + del) x + d y = xsol del + a d
##   so y = a - x
##   (d + del) x + a d - d x = xsol del + ad
##   del x = xsol del
##   so x = xsol

$x = random(1,7,1);
$a = random(1,3,1);
$d = random(1,2,1);
$dd = ( $d == 1 ) ? '' : $d;
$del = random(1,3,1);
$deld = ( $del == 1 ) ? '' : $del;
$c = $d + $del;
$e = $x*$del + $a*$d;

$xsol = Compute( $x );
$ysol = Compute( $x - $a );

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT

Where do the lines \( x - y = $a \) and \( $c x - $dd y = $e \)
intersect?
$BR
Intersection point = (\{ $xsol->ans_rule(10) \}, \{ $ysol->ans_rule(10) \})

END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

ANS( $xsol->cmp() );
ANS( $ysol->cmp() );

$ad = $a*$d;
$xdel = $x*$del;

Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR SOLUTION $PAR

To find the intersection point, we need the \(x\) and \(y\) values
that satisfy the equations.  Solving for \(y\) in the
first equation, we have
\(y = x - $a\).
$PAR
Plugging into the second equation, we have
\[\begin{aligned}
    $c x - $dd(x - $a) &= $e\\
    $deld x + $ad &= $e \\
    $deld x &= $xdel.
\end{aligned}\]
Thus \( x = $x\) and \(y = $x - $a = $ysol\).  The intersection
point is \(($x, $ysol)\).

END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;

ENDDOCUMENT();
